---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import "../styles/global.css";
---

<Layout
  title="Our Story"
  description="Founded in 1986 by Harry Rowe Jr., Big Dipper Ice Cream Parlour has been a Prospect, CT landmark for nearly 40 years. Now a new second location in Seymour, CT."
>
  <!-- Page Hero -->
  <section class="relative h-60 flex items-end overflow-hidden bg-bdteal">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-sprinkle-pattern opacity-30"></div>
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pb-10 w-full">
      <p class="font-script text-white/80 text-xl mb-1">Our Story</p>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl font-bold text-white">About Us</h1>
    </div>
    <svg class="absolute bottom-0 w-full" viewBox="0 0 1200 40" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" preserveAspectRatio="none">
      <path d="M0,40 L0,20 C300,0 600,40 900,20 C1050,10 1150,30 1200,20 L1200,40 Z" fill="#fff8e8"/>
    </svg>
  </section>


  <section class="py-5 max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
  
    <!-- TOP ROW -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start mb-10">
      
      <!-- LEFT: TEXT -->
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-chocolate mb-6">
          Another location, <span class="italic text-bdteal">same great ice cream.</span>
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-5 font-body text-chocolate/80 text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            The Big Dipper Ice Cream Parlour was founded in Prospect, CT in 1986 by Harry Rowe Jr and his wife, Barbara. The original store was located at 52 Waterbury Road and is now at 91 Waterbury Road, Prospect.
          </p>

          <p>
            Now operated by their son Harry Rowe, III, the Big Dipper continues the tradition with over 50 rotating flavors and has won countless awards. The Big Dipper homestyle ice cream is freshly made on the premises in small batches. Their milk is sourced from Kingdom Creamery, a 4th Generation farm in upstate Vermont. This ensures a top quality product every time a customer visits. Adam, is also the owner of Inner City Electrical in Prospect since 2011, a family owned company. Adam brings a wealth of knowledge to the Big Dipper of Seymour and excited to add new additions to the menu.
          </p>

          <p>
            The Big Dipper is celebrating its 40th season this year and is excited to continue Harry and Barbara Rowe's tradition by joining the Seymour community with their second location. Harry is joined by his friend and business partner, Adam Kielcewski, who also shares the same passion for connecting people through their love of ice cream.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- RIGHT: IMAGE -->
      <div class="relative">
        <img
          src="./Owners.png"
          alt="The owners of The Big Dipper"
          class="rounded-3xl shadow-2xl w-full object-cover h-80 lg:h-[32rem]"
        />
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- BOTTOM BANNER IMAGE -->
    <div class="relative">
      <img
        src="./hero.JPG"
        alt="Exterior of The Big Dipper Seymour"
        class="rounded-3xl shadow-2xl w-full object-cover h-72 lg:h-[42rem]"
      />
    </div>

  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
       THE BUILDING
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="bg-cream-100 bg-waffle-pattern py-20">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="text-center mb-14">
        <p class="font-script text-bdteal text-2xl mb-1">Our Home</p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-chocolate">The Building</h2>
        <div class="w-20 h-1 bg-bdteal rounded-full mx-auto mt-4"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-5 font-body text-chocolate/80 text-lg leading-relaxed text-base">
          <p>
            The Turel Whittemore Tavern, dating back to the 1740s, was part of early Seymour when travel happened by horse and carriage and taverns were the heart of the community. Places like this weren't just for food and drink—they were gathering spots where locals met, travelers rested, and news was shared.
          </p>
          <p>
            It was acquired around 1778 by E. Turel Whittemore and served as a tavern. At that point, the building was only one story high. The second story was added in 1867 by Martin Castle, who dismantled the building's old chimney and used the stones to construct the terraced wall in front of the property. On the northwest corner of the old tavern was a barroom, where in 1780 a group of Torries planned the robbery of the home of the Patriot, Capt. Ebenezer Dayton, which was located in Bethany.
          </p>
          <p>
            This infamous incident led to the dramatic kidnapping, in nearby Oxford, of the Patriot boy, Chauncey Judd, a 16-year-old member of the Oxford militia, who ran into the fleeing robbers. They were later captured and sent to Newgate Prison and Judd was freed. Since then, the Tavern has housed several businesses, including an ice cream shoppe for the last 15+ years. From a historic tavern… to The Big Dipper.
          </p>
        </div>

      <div class="py-5 grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8 mb-14">
        <img
          src="./inside.JPG"
          alt="Harry and Barabra Rowe, founders of The Big Dipper"
          class="rounded-3xl shadow-lg object-cover w-full h-110 col-span-1 lg:col-span-2"
        />
        <img
          src="./entrance.JPG"
          alt="Shop detail"
          class="rounded-3xl shadow-lg object-cover h-110 w-full"
        />
      </div>

      <!-- <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
        <div class="space-y-5 font-body text-chocolate/80 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            The building at 123 Sweet Street was constructed in 1924 as a soda fountain and five-and-dime shop. Its original pressed tin ceilings, black-and-white hexagonal tile floor, and the long marble counter top along the east wall have all been lovingly preserved — and still greet customers every single day.
          </p>
          <p>
            During a 1995 renovation, George discovered original blueprints and soda fountain menus from the 1930s tucked behind a wall panel. Those menus now hang framed in the back dining room, a testament to the building's sweet heritage.
          </p>
          <p>
            The pink-and-white striped awning — a landmark recognized by nearly everyone in town — was installed in 1980 and has been faithfully restored every decade since. The neon "ICE CREAM" sign in the window dates to 1983 and still glows every evening at dusk.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-5 font-body text-chocolate/80 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            In 2010, the Whitmore family undertook a major kitchen expansion, adding a proper production space behind the original shop where all 40+ flavors are now made fresh each morning. Visitors are often treated to the sight — and smell — of fresh batches being pulled from the churners through the large glass viewing window.
          </p>
          <p>
            The building was added to the local historic registry in 2018, and the family continues to steward it with the same care they put into every scoop. Today, George and Eleanor's daughter, Caroline, runs the day-to-day operation, with the third generation of Whitmores already spending summers behind the counter.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div> -->
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
       TIMELINE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
